  "editorial": {
    "headline": "Chisholm Late Blast Lifts Yankees Past Red Sox",
    "subheadline": "New York Yankees beats Boston Red Sox.",
    "lead_angle": "Jazz Chisholm Jr. broke a tense eighth-inning deadlock with a towering three-run home run to right field, lifting the New York Yankees to a 6-1 victory over the Boston Red Sox at Yankee Stadium. His blast capped a five-run explosion in the penultimate frame that shattered what had been a tight, pitcher-dominated duel in the Bronx.\n\nBoston had pulled even in the sixth when Ceddanne Rafaela singled and later crossed the plate, but the game turned for good in the bottom of the eighth against reliever Justin Slaten. After New York loaded the bases on a walk and a pair of base hits, Chisholm drove a hanging slider deep into the right-field seats. Cody Bellinger followed with a solo shot of his own to seal it, ensuring reliever Tim Hill earned the victory after throwing a scoreless eighth frame in relief.\n\nTrent Grisham paced the New York lineup by going three-for-four, including a run-scoring single in the fifth, while Paul Goldschmidt also collected two hits. This critical division win keeps New York in prime position for the American League East crown, putting crucial distance between them and their historic rivals as the grueling summer schedule begins to heat up.",
    "reason": "Best game on today's slate."
